thread.title: Girls team tennis - Brookfield East pulls upset; loses in final
thread.title_full: Girls team tennis - Brookfield East pulls upset; loses in final

author: Dave Boehler
title: Girls team tennis - Brookfield East pulls upset; loses in final
text:
Madison — In a matter of minutes Saturday afternoon, Brookfield East went from saving its season by upsetting the top-ranked girls tennis team in the state to playing in its first championship match.
Ninth-ranked East, in the semifinals for the first time since 1994, rallied to stun No. 1 Eau Claire Memorial, 4-3, at the Nielsen Tennis Stadium.
The Spartans, who lost to the Old Abes in the regular season, 6-1, trailed the rematch, 3-1.
But after singles victories by Emily Horneffer (No. 3) and Emma Corwin (No. 1), they advanced thanks to a 6-4, 4-6, 6-0 victory from Carly Wolff over Sierra Auleta at No. 2.
"It's the best feeling ever, knowing my team makes it to the finals, which is unheard of," Wolff said.
Getting to state isn't common, either.
This was just the fourth trip to the tournament for East, which lost in the quarterfinals last season after not competing here since '94 and '95.
And 10 minutes after Wolff's victory, the Spartans were taking on No. 4 Neenah in the final.
One of the first players on the court was East's Claire Davis, who plays No. 3 doubles.
"It was crazy, my heart was beating out of my chest," she said. "I think her winning the match really set the tone. It was like, 'OK, we got this. Let's get out there. Let's go.'"
Like against Memorial, East dropped a 6-1 decision to Neenah earlier this year and also fell behind, 3-1, in the rematch.
The Spartans' magic ran out, however, as they suffered a 4-3 loss. It was the Rockets who won their first state title, one year after losing to Arrowhead in the final.
"Eau Claire was a matchup I thought we could win, and I think the girls believed that," East coach Linda Lied said. "It was pure excitement. But we knew Neenah was good. I told the girls all season I thought Neenah was the best team in the state. I have nothing but the utmost respect for Neenah and the program.
"We knew they were going to be tough. We knew we were a little dipped on energy. We barely got done, and literally 10 minutes later (the WIAA) put our doubles out. That's not a lot of time to rally and pull the troops together."
Corwin agreed.
"Had we maybe a longer break, I think it could've gone either way," she said. "But us in the finals? We were not expecting this."
East was able to cut the deficit to 3-2 after Corwin's 6-3, 6-0 victory over Kiki Risgaard at No. 1 singles, but then Neenah clinched the victory when Jordyn Lawatsch defeated Wolff, 6-4, 6-2. Horneffer then beat Megan Nasr, 4-6, 6-1, 6-2, at No. 3 for the final outcome.
"Nobody expected us to get here except us," Lied said. "I'm really proud of them for that."
DIVISION 2 Madison Edgewood 7, Altoona 0: The top-ranked Crusaders won state for the second time in three years; the No. 5 Railroaders reached their first final.
Since Division 2 was added in 1994, Saturday marked just the second time a Milwaukee-area team did not reach the championship. University School's 11-year run of reaching the tournament ended this season.
